book on engaged Buddhism focuses on women working for social justice in a wide range of Buddhist traditions and societies. Contributors document attempts to actualize Buddhism's liberating ideals of personal growth and social transformation. Dealing with issues such as human rights, gender-based violence, prostitution, and the role of Buddhist nuns, the work illuminates the possibilities for positive change that are available to those with limited power and resources. Integrating social realities and theoretical perspectives, the work utilizes feminist interpretations of Buddhist values and looks at culturally appropriate means of instigating change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBuddhist monasticism and religious orders for women. 0aBuddhist womenxSocial conditions. 0aFeminismxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aSocial justice. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women in Religion. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh1 aChew, Lin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChhabra, Meenakshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoberly, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeVido, Elise Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGellner, David N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Anne Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLama, Khandu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeVine, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorswor